{{Infobox person |name=George Abbitt |birth_date=1634 |birth_place=[[Dorchester, Dorset|Dorchester]], [[England]]<ref name="ahd">[https://books.google.com/books?id=YCgBAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA69#v=onepage&q&f=false An Historical Discourse in Commemoration of the 200th Anniversary of the Settlement of Norwalk]</ref> |death_date=1689 |death_place=[[Norwalk, Connecticut|Norwalk]], [[Connecticut Colony]] |residence=[[Norwalk, Connecticut|Norwalk]], [[Connecticut Colony]] |spouse=Mary Weed (ca. August 1650, [[Windsor, Connecticut|Windsor]], [[Connecticut Colony]]; Johanna Williamson<ref name="norw">[https://books.google.com/books?id=FulEAAAAYAAJ&lpg=PA345&ots=fuYDnmKe_Q&dq=George%20Abbott%20norwalk&pg=PA345#v=onepage&q=George%20Abbott%20norwalk&f=false Norwalk: v. 1 and supplement, Volume 1]</ref> |children=George Abbott, Dorcas Abbott, John Abbott, Priscilla Abbott, Mary Abbott, Jonathan Abbott, Daniel Abbott; and by his second wife, James, Elizabeth, and Sarah<ref name="norw"/> }}
'''George Abbitt''' (also '''George Abbott''') (1634–1689) was a founding settler of [[Norwalk, Connecticut|Norwalk]], [[Connecticut]].
He was the son of Maurice and Gertrude Abbott of England.
He originally settled in [[Windsor, Connecticut|Windsor]], as an [[indentured servant]]. He apparently was sanctioned for selling ammunition to the natives, which was a serious offence at the time. He later settled in [[Hartford, Connecticut|Hartford]], and then prior to 1655, he settled in Norwalk.<ref name="norw"/>
He is listed on the Founders Stone bearing the names of the [[History of Norwalk, Connecticut|founders of Norwalk]] in the [[East Norwalk Historical Cemetery]].
